# **6. Why does this work?**

Since both lists are already sorted,

The smallest remaining element is always at the front of either `list1` or `list2`.

By always choosing the smaller front node,

The merged list remains sorted.

When one list finishes,

The remaining nodes in the other list are already sorted,

So we can attach them directly.

---

# **7. Java Code**

```java
class Solution {

    public ListNode mergeTwoLists(ListNode list1, ListNode list2) {

        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(-1);
        ListNode tail = dummy;

        while (list1 != null && list2 != null) {

            if (list1.val <= list2.val) {
                tail.next = list1;
                list1 = list1.next;
            } else {
                tail.next = list2;
                list2 = list2.next;
            }

            tail = tail.next;
        }

        if (list1 != null)
            tail.next = list1;

        if (list2 != null)
            tail.next = list2;

        return dummy.next;
    }
}
```

---

# **8. Time Complexity**

**O(m + n)**

* `m` = number of nodes in `list1`
* `n` = number of nodes in `list2`

Each node is visited exactly once.

---

# **9. Space Complexity**

**O(1)**

No extra list is created.

We only use a dummy node and a few pointers.

---

# **10. Important Interview Note**

The **dummy node** is a common linked list technique that simplifies handling the head of the merged list. It avoids special cases for the first node.

Also, this solution **reuses the existing nodes** instead of creating new ones, making it both time-efficient and space-efficient.

---

# **11. One-line Note for Interviews**

**Use a dummy node and compare the front nodes of both sorted lists. Attach the smaller node each time, then append the remaining nodes after one list becomes empty.** 🚀
